C.T. Sandon &amp; Co. appear to have vacated 310 George St by mid April 1889...and I'd say that if this were the case, then Sandon's sign wouldn't have remained up much beyond this date ('To Builders, Contractors, and Others', towards top of column 4) - <a href="http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13732292" rel="nofollow">nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13732292</a> ; 310 George St had evidently changed hands in July 1888 (3rd item, column 3) - <a href="http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13691478" rel="nofollow">nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13691478</a> ; 

I can't get any digitised newspaper hits for the American Studio at 310 George St after 1885, which might or might not be significant...

Per this item, the removal of scaffolding at the GPO tower was completed in mid March 1886...in this pic we can see one of the beams left in the tower by the contractors for hoisting the bells when the time came (item top of column 4) - <a href="http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13614555" rel="nofollow">nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13614555</a> ; ... of course in this pic we can only see the top of the GPO tower, so we can't tell whether all the scaffolding had been removed at the time the pic was taken...however, per the SMH item, the removal of the scaffolding took under 2 months...if this were the case, then we can be fairly certain that this pic must have been taken after mid/late January 1886...hardly a revelation, but it's at least a firm 'earliest date'.
